title: For Sale:  Marlin 336W 30-30 NIB
postcontent: This made in the USA rifle is brand new in the box with everything the factory sent it out with including all the paperwork, gunlock, owners book, and a padded Realtree sling. It has nice walnut wood with satin blue metal finish on the barrel and receiver. One of the most stealthy steel frame finishes, the color sets this rifle apart from other models, without the bright “Here I am!” of the brass and silver rifles. In the woods, where they’re right at home, the non reflective bluing, and walnut wood form their own basic camouflage that your Great Grandpa would have been very familiar with while hunting deer, and we like to think he would have been quite appreciative to have this Marlin along. Merging old with new, the profile is conventional, and the caliber is also long-established. The .30-30 dates back to 1894, and while it may be considered ancient today, the modern hunter can handle anything from coyote to deer, with the right load. It features adjustable buckhorn and bead sights, and checkered walnut furniture. title: For Sale:  1937 Norton VELOCETTE KSS
postcontent: Other manufacturers were fielding new overhead-valve and overhead-camshaft machines, and Veloce Ltd followed suit with the Percy Goodman-designed, overhead-cam Model K first appearing in 1924. Of 348cc, the new engine employed a single overhead camshaft driven by vertical shaft, and was unusual in having a very narrow crankcase, an arrangement determined by the existing transmission and frame design, which made for a stiff crankshaft assembly. Entered in the 1925 Isle of Man TT, the new model K did not fare well, all three entries retiring because of lubrication problems. Its engine redesigned to incorporate dry-sump oiling, the 'cammy' Velo returned the following year to score a memorable victory, Alec Bennett romping home in the Junior race 10 minutes ahead of the second-place rider! Second place in 1927 followed by another win for Bennett in 1928 ensured a healthy demand for Velocette's overhead-cam roadsters and prompted the launch of the KTT, one of the most successful over-the-counter racers of all time. Introduced in 1925, the KSS was the Super Sports version. For the 1936 season, the MkII version of the KSS represented a major redesign, featuring a new aluminium-alloy cylinder head with enclosed valve-gear, plus the cradle frame and heavyweight Webb forks of the new MSS.
